## Read First

1. Read `AGENTS.md` first for Directory Architecture, Agent Roster, Security & Audit Matrix, Threat Model, Architecture Decisions, ADR Index, Quality Gates, and artifact tracking.
2. Use `.gemini/agents/*.md` local subagents when a task matches their `description`.
3. Keep fan-out in this root Gemini session. Gemini subagents cannot recursively call other subagents; cross-agent work returns here.
4. Do not write `mcp_servers:` or extension MCP config unless the MCP approval gate has shown and approved the exact YAML or JSON block.
5. Follow `AGENTS.md` › **Memory & Learning System**. Gemini subagents propose Learning Check entries; this root session or the orchestrator owns memory writes.

## Local Subagents

- Project agents: `.gemini/agents/<name>.md`
- User agents: `~/.gemini/agents/<name>.md`
- Required frontmatter: `name`, `description`
- Default kind: `local`
- MCP key: `mcp_servers` (snake_case)

## Canonical Context

Load `AGENTS.md` for the full project memory and treat this file as a Gemini-native pointer. If this file is a copy rather than a symlink, regenerate it whenever the managed `AGENTS.md` block changes.

## Memory & Learning

- Canonical policy: `AGENTS.md` › **Memory & Learning System**.
- Learning Check before done: `none | proposed_new:<id> | proposed_update:<id> | deferred:<reason>`.
- Do not store secrets or raw credentials in learnings.
- Do not write memory directly from Gemini subagents unless they explicitly own the memory path.

